title: Cross sections and thick target yields of (alpha,pxn) reactions on natural platinum.

reactions on natural platinum.

x4freetext: The reactions were used
to  determine the beam incident energy and to calculate
the alpha-particles flux.
The fluxes obtained through both standard functions
differ only in 1%, whereas the error in its
determination is less than 11%.
The targets were assembled according to the
stacked-foils method. Cu-foils were put between the Pt-
foils. The Pt-foils were analyzed spectroscopically,
the quantities of impurities were negligible. The
surface density of these foils was 18.9-mg/cm**2,
whereas the one corresponding to Cu was 28.8 mg/cm**2.
Each one of the foils constititing a target was wrapped
in Al of surface density 3.72-mg/cm**2, in order to
avoid the loss of radioactive nuclei by recoiling.
An intrinsic Ge-detector of high resolution-
Beam intensity was varied between 5 and 8
microAmperes.
The yields of thick targets were calculated
and a comparison between the cross sections obtained
using the hybrid model of pre-equilibrium reactions in
combination with the statistical model of compound
nucleus is presented.

x4freetext: see COMMENT
-By authors.  Order to detect the presence of 194-Au,
the 328.4 KeV photopeak was followed.  It is
interesting to note that 194-g-Ir (19.15hr) and
194-m-Ir(171days) decay through the same excited level
of 194-Pt, therefore, the analyzed ray is shared by
three istopes.  As the measurements were done 9 days
after the end of the irradiation, the contributions of
the 194-g-Ir may be neglected.  The contributions of
the isomer of 171 days may be neglected too since the
measurements lasted not more than 10 minutes.  The
194-Au is fed by its parent, 194Hg (260 years), and
this additional formation was subtracted.  This
correction is neglected due to the very long period of
the mother.
/by Compiler/ To get presentation of cr.section in
usual form, someone should multiplying values on the
average atomic mass of target (in this case: ~ 195.06)

x4freetext: see COMMENT
-By authors.  The decay of 195(m+g)Au (183 d) was
studied considering the gamma-ray 98.9 KeV.  There are
three more isotopes which by their disintegration
populate the same excited level of 195-Pt:  195-m-Ir
(3.8 hours), 195-g-Ir (2.5 hours) and 195-m-pt (4.02
days).  These isotopes are neglected since they were
measured forty days after the end of irradiation.  As
regards 195 Au, obtained from the decay of 195-m-Hg and
195-g-Hg, the contributions of the 41.6 hours isomer
was the only one that could be discounted.  The other
contributions could not be taken into account, since
the excitation function for 195-g-Hg was not available.

x4freetext: see COMMENT
-  By authors.  The activities of 196(m+g)-Au (8.1 sec,
6.18 days) were determined by means of the photopeak of
426.1 KeV and 355.7 KeV.  The contribution of the
196-Ir (52 S, 1.4 hour) isomer to the 355.7 KeV
gamma-ray was not considered since the measurements
were done 9 days after the irradiation.  By the way,
the 196-Hg and 196-Pt isotopes are stable and therefore
they do not lead to the formation of 196-Au.
Nevertheless,  there exists an isomeric state of 196-Au
(9.7 hours), which decays by isomeric transition to an
8.2 seconds isomer and afterwards to the ground state .
These contributions could not be subtracted since the
cross sections for this isomer were unknown.

x4freetext: see COMMENT
-By authors.  The disintegration of 198-g Au was
followed by the photopeak of 411.8 KeV the only
discount done is the one corresponding to the
contribution of the 2.3 days isomer.  The isotope
191-Pt (2.8 days) decays emitting a gamma-ray of 409.4
KeV, which cannot be separated from the
gamma-corresponding to 198-g-Au by the detector used in
the  measurements.  Nevertheless, by means of the cross
sections of 191-Pt, it could be verified that the 409.4
keV photopeak only contributes 2% to the whole area.

x4freetext: see COMMENT
-By authors.  The activities of 199-Au were calculated
with the areas obtained in the measurement of the
photopeak of 158.4 keV.  This gamma-deexcitation is
shared by the 199m-Hg (42.6 min) in its decay to 199Hg,
but at the time of the measurements it was completely
decayed.  On the other hand, the 199-Pt isotope feeds
the main isotope and this discount could not be
performed because the corresponding excitation function
was not available.  In spite of this difficulty, the
formation of this isotope is believed to be of no
importance since it is only obtained by the (alpha,2pn)
reaction on 198-Pt, its isotopic abundance in the
irradiated target being only 7.2%.
